        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-container">
            <h3>Is a percentage decrease just a negative percentage increase?</h3>
            <p>Conceptually, yes. The core math operates via the exact same "Absolute Change / Original Value" framework. If a stock drops from $100 to $90, it is a 10% percentage decrease, which can also be denoted on a spreadsheet as a -10% percentage increase.</p>
            
            <h3>Why do I get the wrong answer when I divide by the new number?</h3>
            <p>Percentage logic is anchored to the chronological starting point. A drop from 100 to 50 is a 50% decrease. If you incorrectly divide by 50, you generate a 100% false reading. The denominator must always be the historical original value.</p>
            
            <h3>How do I reverse a percentage decrease?</h3>
            <p>Reversing a percentage decline requires a larger percentage increase to recover the absolute loss. If your $100 investment suffers a 50% decrease down to $50, you actually need a 100% increase on that new $50 just to get back to your $100 baseline.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Mastering how to calculate percentage decrease grants you the mathematical clarity required to truly understand sales performance, discount retail shopping, and economic asset depreciation. By memorizing the core formula, properly locking your denominator to the original starting value, and utilizing digital calculators for speedy large-scale assessments, you can analyze numerical drops confidently in any environment.</p>
